Confirmed — and the code makes the mechanism sharper than the other chat could prove from outside. It's a true spook.

## The proof

`jjrsc_scout.rs` nests the *entire* search inside the per-pace loop:

```rust
for (heat_key, heat) in &gallops.heats {        // all heats, no status filter
    for coronet_key in &heat.order {            // ← per-PACE
        ...
        } else {
            // paddock is read HERE, inside the pace loop
            let paddock_path = jjri_paddock_path(...);
            if let Ok(content) = fs::read_to_string(&paddock_path) { ... }
        }
    }
}
```

A pace-less heat has an empty `heat.order`, so the inner loop body **never executes** — the paddock is never even read. That's exactly ₣BH (0 paces). The other chat's "proven" claim is correct, and its "not proven" hypothesis is now proven: scout is pace-keyed, and the paddock search lives *inside* the pace iteration.

## Two corrections/bonuses the code reveals

1. **Stabled exclusion is definitively not the cause.** Line 64 iterates "racing, stabled, retired" with no status check — so the ₣A- counter-evidence was right, status is never consulted.
2. **The bug is broader than zero-pace heats.** The paddock sits in the `else` of an `if silks / else if text / else if direction / else paddock` chain. So even for a heat *with* paces, if every pace matches on its own silks/text/direction, the paddock is never searched. And when it is searched, it's re-read from disk once per pace (redundant I/O) and the match gets hung on whichever pace happened to fall through — which is why the other chat saw paddock excerpts attached to pace rows.

## Fix shape

Hoist the paddock search out of the pace loop into a **once-per-heat** search, independent of pace count. When only the paddock matches, emit a **heat-level row** (heat header + paddock excerpt, no coronet). That single move fixes all three: pace-less heats become visible, all-paces-match heats surface paddock hits, and the redundant per-pace re-reads disappear.

Want me to slate this into ₣BD alongside the validate pace? The docket would lock: paddock search is per-heat not per-pace; paddock-only matches render as a heat-level row; the `actionable` filter still applies only to pace rows (a paddock isn't actionable). Point at `jjrsc_scout.rs` and let mount decide the rendering.
